│ assertion failure occurs in `ScheduleData::incrementUnscheduledDeps()` when `hasValidDependencies()` returns false but we're trying to decrement unscheduled dependencies. This happens during control         │
│ dependency processing. The `DecrUnsched` lambda at line 5403 checks `(IsControl || Data->hasValidDependencies())` before calling `incrementUnscheduledDeps()`. However, `incrementUnscheduledDeps()` asserts   │
│ that `hasValidDependencies()` must be true, regardless of `IsControl`. This is a contradiction: the condition allows control dependencies to proceed even when dependencies aren't valid, but the method       │
│ requires them to be valid.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows that the crash occurs when processing control dependencies for `%call = tail call i32 (ptr, ...) @printf(ptr null, i32 %add1)`. This     │
│ instruction is marked as `[Copyable]` and appears to have been scheduled already. The debug output shows `reset schedule because   %call = tail call i32 (ptr, ...) @printf(ptr null, i32 %add1) was already   │
│ scheduled`. This suggests the instruction might have been scheduled in a previous bundle, and now we're trying to process it again.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: Control dependencies can be added to            │
│ instructions that don't have their regular dependency information calculated yet (i.e., `hasValidDependencies()` returns false). This happens because control dependencies are calculated based on instruction │
│ properties (like calls that may not return) rather than data dependencies. When we later try to decrement these control dependencies during scheduling, we hit the assertion.\n\n   The issue is in the        │
│ interaction between:\n   - Line 5403-5404: `if ((IsControl || Data->hasValidDependencies()) && Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0)`\n   - Line 4773: `assert(hasValidDependencies() && \"increment of     │
│ unscheduled deps would be meaningless\");`\n\n   When `IsControl` is true but `hasValidDependencies()` is false, we pass the condition but fail the assertion.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): \n   a) In        │
│ `ScheduleData::incrementUnscheduledDeps()` (lines 4772-4777), remove the assertion and handle the invalid case gracefully by returning the current `UnscheduledDeps` without modification.\n   b) In           │
│ `ScheduleCopyableData::incrementUnscheduledDeps()` (lines 5044-5050), apply the same fix.\n\n   The fix should be:\n   ```cpp\n   int incrementUnscheduledDeps(int Incr) {\n     if                            │
│ (!hasValidDependencies())\n       return UnscheduledDeps;\n     UnscheduledDeps += Incr;\n     return UnscheduledDeps;\n   }\n   ```\n   This preserves the existing behavior for instructions with valid      │
│ dependencies, and gracefully handles instructions without valid dependencies (like control dependency targets). The `UnscheduledDeps` field will remain at `InvalidDeps` (-1) for such instructions, ensuring  │
│ they never become ready (which is correct since they're not part of the scheduling graph).\n\n5. Conclusion: The assertion is too restrictive for control dependencies. By removing it and returning early     │
│ when dependencies aren't valid, we allow control dependency processing to complete without affecting scheduling correctness. The instructions without valid dependencies will remain unscheduled, which        │
│ matches their original status outside the vectorization scheduling region."})                                                                                                                                  │
